<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Richard Brooks LCGI, MIET</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC19</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Richard Brooks LCGI, MIET</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> qualified as an electrician </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">having studied</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in an FE college over 5 years attending evening classes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as a mature student</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. This was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> supported by working in industry. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ompleted Electrical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Installation qualifications to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Level 4 and hold</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a Licentiateship in Electrical Installation from the City and Guilds. Entered Further Education 15 years ago to train new electricians and have contributed to several national organisations involved in the in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dustry. This submission represents my own </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">view.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the extent to which members of the public are aware of the competent persons scheme and that certain domestic electrical works need to be reviewed and certified to meet the requirements of Building Regulation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a householder I do not recall ever being sent any literature promoting these schemes, I have never seen an advert on television or in a local paper advertising any of these schemes. More preval</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ent and much more pro-active</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> schemes such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">check-a-tr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ade</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> where quality and professionalism of work is promoted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are definitely visible to the householder</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">You will see electricians vans advertising that they are members of various organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but these do not have any impact without sufficient promotion of their meaning. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The prevalence of electrical products available in DIY stores who also supply ‘How to guides’ for electrical installation work gives the householder the impression that elec</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tricity is not as dangerous and whilst disclaimers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> may be on the li</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">terature these are not necessarily prominent or helpful.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the extent to which those carrying out electrical works are adequately trained to meet the requirements of the Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and the extent to which all those working for a company are brought up to the same level of skills; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Part P had honourable intentions in that it was a defined scope scheme. This allowed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tradespersons such as plumbers, who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for example </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">needed to access the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> electrical system to connect up a boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">permission to do this level</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of limited work. Correctly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> qualified plumbers should</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be able to carry out such works. The scheme </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">then </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">meant to limit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> more intensive work to those fully qualified and competent in electrical installation. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">When Part P was first introduced a qualification was developed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by an awarding body</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that had various modules relevant to elements of Part P which supported qualified t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rades persons in refreshing and extending their knowledge. The intention was that these individual modules would be studied according to need but that these would supplement their full trade specific qualifications. However some training centres chose to m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arket the achievement of all the modules as being ‘Part P’ qualified inferring that they could carry out all electrical installation work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in a domestic property</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The term ‘5 day wonders’ has developed in industry which encompasses any person trading as an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">electrician who does not hold suitable qualifications or competence to register themselves as an electrician with the JIB but are able to obtain full scope status with one of the accreditation bodies.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Electrical Industry already had an electrotechnica</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l certification scheme administered by the JIB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://www.jib.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.jib.org.uk/</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. There are various grades available but full electrician status will not be granted unless you can demonstrate that you are a fully qualified elec</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">trician with an NVQ Level 3 which demonstrates full competency in electrical installation. To achieve an NVQ candidates will be visited on site many times over a reasonably lengthy period of time and will have demonstrated on at least 3 occasions they are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">competent in e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> aspect of electrical installation. They will also have had to pass a 3 day trade test that covers critical safety aspects of the industry.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My understanding is that the competency scheme providers are giving full scope status to individua</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ls who cannot demonstrate this level of education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or competency</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the extent to which those carrying out electrical works, to which the Building Regulations apply, review or have their work reviewed to ensure that it meets the requirements of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Regulations;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the adequacy of the review of electrical works carried out by Competent Persons;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is my understanding that yearly checks are made by the competency scheme providers. Whilst I cannot comment on the quality of these checks there is a commercial interest in the individual passing and registering with that company. This is not a healthy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">approach to ensuring safety. A free market approach to such a scheme would only be sufficiently rigourous if there was a requirement for individuals to pass tests administered by other independent organisations such as the ACS assessments carried out by in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dividuals wishing to join the gas safe register.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the effect of competition between accreditation bodies, and the two separate registers of electricians, on the standards of review of domestic electrical work; and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the adequacy of the supervision by DCLG o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">f the accreditation schemes. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I believe that the effect of competition between accreditation bodies has seriously undermined the industry and put more householders at risk than ever before. Whilst statistics may show that safety has improved this is more likely to do with the advances </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the products being used as the old rubber sheathed cable that degrades has been replaced with PVC sheathed cable and protective devices such as re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">able fuses are replaced by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Miniature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> circuit breakers and Residual current devices.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am not aware of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> any electrician who has had their registration with a competency scheme having their work checked independently or their registration process audited by the DCLG.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In summary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– the current scheme allows the Part P certification </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scheme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providers to apply l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ess rigorous standards than those defined by the Sector Skills Council responsible for the industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Having more the one scheme provider means that the level of standard required may be interpreted differently by these organisations with membership of some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being far easier than others.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can allow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> operatives who have not demonstrated sufficient competency or evidence of sufficient training to carry out electrical installation work. This can only lead to installations being installed that are inherently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not safe.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even the suggestion of an umbrella list/register that all persons registered with the various scheme providers automatically belong to will not address the issues raised by the committee. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">16 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>